Date:2/26/2004 8:31:19 AM
From:Joe Dancy
Berkshire's Charlie Munger on value investing

Here's a book review on Damn Right, a study of Munger's investment philosophy.
The guy does not mind volatility since his value bent serves as a floor to his
portfolio. His investors had a ride however, the guy concentrated his bets into
a few names he found attractive.

http://www.financialsense.com/fsu/posts/dancy/reviews/022504.html

With all the Enron style accounting fiascos I'm not sure concentrating bets is
the way to go these days - if you can trust the numbers it might be - but if
one company "blows up" due to falsified financials it can really hurt a
portfolio.
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:2/26/2004 8:36:00 AM
From:Joe Dancy
Value based portfolio

For what it is worth we look for value plays that have growth characteristics
that also meet some fundamental TA characteristics - the best of all worlds.
High relative strength, low p/s ratio, high revenue and EPS growth rates. And
an inefficient niche - small firms. FWIW our portfolio is on page two of the
attached report:

http://lsgifund.com/lsgireport/LSGI_Report_Feb_2004.pdf

We use screens to find these firms - otherwise the pile of interesting firms to
research is just too large. Statistically they should outperform longer term,
but are volatile as heck - which is good on the way up and bad on the way down.
FWIW
%EOM----------------------

