Date:2/26/2004 8:44:29 PM
From:Steve168
Joe, It has been a long time I did not see your post. Glad you are back and
thanks for the nice review on the Munger book.

I am trying to use a similar approach as yours - find value plays with growth
characteristics, once the growth become real, hold on to it, don't just sell at
"fair value".

My largest holding ALVR in Feb2003 was ALVR, trading at $1.86 with $3.3
cash/share, no debt, cash burn rate 8cent/Q and improving. Later the growth
turned out to be real, and I revised sell target multiple times just in time to
hold on(I recommended on this board at 1.86, later around 3, 5, 8) - still have
majority of shares now at $14.30. It was a "Value Investor's Dream Come
True!!!!"

I held two other home run stocks before, bought PHTN at cash value $3 and sold
$65 in two years, bought SINA at cash value $1.5 and unloaded at 10, 20, 38,
still hold some at 43 now.

Overall my modified value investing approach (hold the fast growers and watch
long-term market momentum) had significantly improved my return comparing with
if I were using regular "sell at fair value" approach, portfolio returned 180%
in 2003 without using margin, option or futures, just long/short common stocks.
Die-hard Ben Graham style investors may predict I will fail sometime. But I
insist on this modification. Warren Buffett's many great stocks picks were not
accepted by Graham while Buffett worked in his partnership, which eventually
led to Buffett's quit. Buffett's modification to "value" was instrumental to
his great success - such as the American Express name brand play. How many
Graham style value stocks are available today that do not have significant
problems? probably none today.

Good Luck and Keep in touch!
%EOM----------------------

